      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between the penultimate and final mesh refinement levels. Richardson extrapolation applied.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted with element sizes 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.35 mm. The GCI between the two finest meshes was 0.8% for stiffness, 1.1% for yield force, and 1.3% for force at 40 mm, all below the 2% criterion. Richardson extrapolation confirmed monotonic convergence. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force residuals converge below 1e-5 relative norm; energy residuals below 1e-4 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged with force residual norms below 5e-6 and energy residuals below 3e-5. No diverged increments were observed. Time-step bisection was not required in any of the 11 specimen simulations. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent review of model setup by a second analyst; checklist-based verification of boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions.",
      "rationale": "A second FDA analyst independently reviewed boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and contact pair definitions against the simulation plan SP-CDRH-2023-041. No discrepancies were identified. A formal use-error checklist (18 items) was completed and archived. Achieved level 2 meets required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear-elastic model with nonlinear geometry (large displacement) and frictional contact is appropriate for the F1717 loading regime below yield; model form uncertainty quantified via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct under F1717 compression-bending is dominated by bending of the rod and screw shank; continuum elasticity with large-displacement kinematics and frictional contact (mu=0.2, Ti-alloy on UHMWPE) captures the dominant physics. A sensitivity study varying friction coefficient ±50% produced <3% change in stiffness QoI, confirming low model-form sensitivity. Plasticity was included for yield force prediction using bilinear isotropic hardening. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test articles; uncertainty in inputs propagated via Monte Carlo (N=500).",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V ELI elastic modulus and yield strength were measured from tensile coupons cut from the same rod lot used in bench testing (E=114.2 GPa, σy=896 MPa). UHMWPE vertebral body block properties from literature with ±15% uncertainty bounds. CMM measurements confirmed screw geometry within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Monte Carlo propagation (N=500) yielded coefficient of variation on stiffness QoI of 3.2%, consistent with experimental scatter. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test articles from production lots; dimensional verification by CMM; material certification traceable to mill certificate.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-representative components. All screws were dimensionally verified by CMM; all rods were from a single certified lot with mill certificate. Constructs were assembled by trained technicians following the surgical technique guide. N=11 exceeds the minimum of 10 specified in the acceptance criteria. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span at least two loading rates and two fixture configurations representative of the COU; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) controlled and recorded.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single quasi-static loading rate (5 mm/min) at ambient laboratory conditions (22±1°C, 45±5% RH) in accordance with ASTM F1717-15. Only one loading rate was employed, which does not span the range of intraoperative loading rates. This single-condition limitation reduces the achieved level to 2, below the required level of 3. This gap is noted as an accepted residual limitation given that ASTM F1717 prescribes a single quasi-static rate and dynamic testing was outside the scope of the current submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test article and fixture conditions; traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was constructed from CAD files of the production screw and rod, confirmed against CMM measurements. Material properties were taken from lot-specific coupon data. Fixture boundary conditions replicated ASTM F1717 loading block geometry as measured by CMM. A traceability matrix (TM-CDRH-2023-055) maps each FEA input to its experimental source. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval computed for all three QoIs; graphical overlay of force-displacement curves; statistical equivalence assessed via two one-sided tests (TOST) at α=0.05.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed as 0.81 (stiffness), 0.67 (yield force), and 1.12 (force at 40 mm), all below 1.96. Force-displacement curve overlays show good morphological agreement across all 11 specimens. TOST analysis confirmed equivalence for all three QoIs at α=0.05 with equivalence bounds of ±10%. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory acceptance criteria for spinal implant constructs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spine and is a direct surrogate for adjacent-segment stress. Yield force is the primary structural integrity metric for FDA 510(k) submissions for pedicle screw systems. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure scenarios. All three QoIs are explicitly listed in FDA guidance for ASTM F1717 submissions. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same screw design, rod diameter, and ASTM F1717 protocol as the intended submission; laboratories are qualified and independent.",
      "rationale": "The validation campaign used the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, 5.5 mm Ti-6Al-4V rod, and ASTM F1717-15 protocol as the regulatory submission. Testing was split across two independent qualified laboratories (FDA CDRH and an ISO 17025-accredited external facility) to assess inter-laboratory reproducibility. The COU is compression-bending prediction for this specific construct, and the validation activities directly address this COU without extrapolation. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    }
